### 4.6 SQL: `provider_business_details` anlegen + Daten migrieren + Spalten droppen

> Da die DB frisch ist (keine Produktionsdaten), sind Migration und Drop ein einzelner Block.
> Bei einer DB mit Daten würde man zuerst die Daten rüber-INSERTen, dann droppen.

```sql
-- Schritt 1: Neue Tabelle anlegen
CREATE TABLE provider_business_details (
  provider_profile_id UUID PRIMARY KEY
    REFERENCES provider_profiles(id) ON DELETE CASCADE,

  -- Legal & Tax
  business_tax_number         TEXT,
  business_vat_number         TEXT,
  business_court_registration TEXT,
  is_business_registered      BOOLEAN,
  business_type               TEXT,   -- einzelunternehmen | gbr | gmbh | ug | freelancer | other

  -- Dokumente
  certificates                JSON,
  license_documents           JSON,

  -- Legal Texte (werden selten abgefragt, können groß sein)
  impressum                   TEXT,
  privacy_policy              TEXT,
  terms_conditions            TEXT,

  -- Registrierte Geschäftsadresse (≠ Servicestandort in provider_profiles)
  business_street             TEXT,
  business_house_number       TEXT,
  business_city               TEXT,
  business_postal_code        TEXT,
  address_line2               TEXT,

  -- Inhaber-Daten (nur für Stripe KYC, nie user-facing)
  owner_first_name            TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '',  -- NOT NULL wie in provider_profiles
  owner_last_name             TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT '',  -- NOT NULL wie in provider_profiles
  owner_date_of_birth         TEXT,

  -- Onboarding
  accepted_provider_terms_at  TIMESTAMPTZ,

  -- Finanz-Settings (nur Admin / Steuerberater)
  invoice_settings            JSON,
  payout_schedule             TEXT,
  minimum_payout_amount       NUMERIC,

  created_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW(),
  updated_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT NOW()
);

-- Schritt 2: Für jeden existierenden Provider-Eintrag einen Detail-Eintrag anlegen
-- (Da frische DB: nur die Struktur, keine echten Daten)
-- Bei Daten: INSERT INTO provider_business_details SELECT ... FROM provider_profiles;

-- Schritt 3: Spalten aus provider_profiles droppen
ALTER TABLE provider_profiles
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_tax_number,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_vat_number,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_court_registration,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS is_business_registered,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_type,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS certificates,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS license_documents,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS impressum,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS privacy_policy,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS terms_conditions,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_street,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_house_number,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_city,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS business_postal_code,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS address_line2,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS owner_first_name,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS owner_last_name,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS owner_date_of_birth,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS accepted_provider_terms_at,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS invoice_settings,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS payout_schedule,
  DROP COLUMN IF EXISTS minimum_payout_amount;
```

**Wie im Backend joinen (wenn nötig):**
```sql
-- Nur bei Onboarding / Admin / Steuerberater:
SELECT pp.*, pbd.*
FROM provider_profiles pp
LEFT JOIN provider_business_details pbd ON pbd.provider_profile_id = pp.id
WHERE pp.id = $1;

-- Normaler Listing-Query: kein JOIN, kein Overhead
SELECT * FROM provider_profiles WHERE id = $1;
```

---

### 4.7 `profiles` → FK Constraint zu `users`

```sql
-- profiles.id und users.id teilen dieselbe UUID
-- Registrierung erstellt ZUERST users, DANN profiles (in einer Transaction)

ALTER TABLE profiles
  ADD CONSTRAINT fk_profiles_users
  FOREIGN KEY (id) REFERENCES users(id) ON DELETE CASCADE;
```

> **Wichtig – Überlappende Felder:**
> Sowohl `users` als auch `profiles` haben `email`, `email_verified`, `is_banned`.
> **Source of Truth ist immer `users`.**
> Die Felder in `profiles` bleiben für Backward-Compat bis alle API-Queries
> auf `users` umgestellt sind – dann Spalten aus `profiles` droppen.

| Feld             | Source of Truth | `profiles` Spalte |
|------------------|-----------------|-------------------|
| `email`          | `users.email`   | Redundant → droppen nach Migration |
| `email_verified` | `users.email_verified` | Redundant → droppen nach Migration |
| `is_banned`      | `users.is_banned` | Redundant → droppen nach Migration |

---

### 4.8 PostgreSQL Triggers

```sql
-- updated_at automatisch setzen
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION update_updated_at()
RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  NEW.updated_at = NOW();
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;

-- Auf alle relevanten Tabellen anwenden
CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON users
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON profiles
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON provider_profiles
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON provider_business_details
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON bookings
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON services
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

CREATE TRIGGER set_updated_at BEFORE UPDATE ON invoices
  FOR EACH ROW EXECUTE FUNCTION update_updated_at();

-- Atomares Claim für Cron Jobs (Race Condition Schutz)
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION claim_next_pending(p_table TEXT)
RETURNS TABLE(id UUID, data JSONB) AS $$
BEGIN
  RETURN QUERY EXECUTE format('
    UPDATE %I SET status = ''processing'', claimed_at = NOW()
    WHERE id = (
      SELECT id FROM %I WHERE status = ''pending''
      ORDER BY created_at ASC LIMIT 1
      FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED
    )
    RETURNING id, to_jsonb(%I.*) AS data
  ', p_table, p_table, p_table);
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql;
```

