### 4.10 PostgreSQL Tuning (postgresql.conf – CX33 spezifisch)

> Angepasst auf 8 GB RAM, 4 vCPU, SSD. Einmalig setzen, dann `reload`.

```ini
# /etc/postgresql/16/main/postgresql.conf

# ── Memory ────────────────────────────────────────────
shared_buffers               = 2GB      # 25% des RAMs
effective_cache_size         = 6GB      # 75% des RAMs
work_mem                     = 64MB     # pro Sort/Hash – bei 200 Connections max ~12 GB
maintenance_work_mem         = 512MB    # für VACUUM, REINDEX
wal_buffers                  = 64MB

# ── Checkpoint ────────────────────────────────────────
checkpoint_completion_target = 0.9
min_wal_size                 = 256MB
max_wal_size                 = 2GB

# ── SSD-spezifisch (Standard ist 4.0 = HDD) ──────────
random_page_cost             = 1.1
effective_io_concurrency     = 200

# ── Parallelism (= vCPU Anzahl) ───────────────────────
max_worker_processes         = 4
max_parallel_workers         = 4
max_parallel_workers_per_gather = 2

# ── Autovacuum (aggressiver als Standard) ─────────────
autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor  = 0.05
autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.02
autovacuum_vacuum_cost_limit    = 400
```

```bash
# Anwenden ohne Neustart
sudo systemctl reload postgresql
```

---

### 4.11 Per-Table Autovacuum (Hot Tables)

Diese drei Tabellen wachsen am schnellsten – aggressivere Schwellwerte verhindern Table Bloat.

```sql
-- bookings: viele Status-Updates
ALTER TABLE bookings SET (
  autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor  = 0.01,
  autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.005
);

-- notifications: wird massenhaft geschrieben und gelesen
ALTER TABLE notifications SET (
  autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor  = 0.02,
  autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.01
);

-- messages: Echtzeit-Schreibrate
ALTER TABLE messages SET (
  autovacuum_vacuum_scale_factor  = 0.02,
  autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.01
);
```

